dot((2,1));
label("$B$",(2,1),E);
[/asy]

response:
 We can use the Pythagorean Theorem in three dimensions to find the length of the diagonal.
Let $d$ be the length of the diagonal. Then,
\begin{align*}
d^2 &= (10)^2 + (20)^2 + (10)^2 \\
&= 100 + 400 + 100 \\
&= 600.
\end{align*}
Taking the square root of both sides, we have
\begin{align*}
d &= \sqrt{600} \\
&= \sqrt{100\cdot6} \\
&= \sqrt{100}\cdot\sqrt{6} \\
&= 10\sqrt{6}.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the length of the diagonal is $\boxed{10\sqrt{6}}$ inches.
The answer is: 10\sqrt{6}

