draw(cone,backpen=dashed);

[/asy]

response:
 Solution:
The volume of a cylinder is given by $V=\pi r^2 h$, where $r$ is the radius and $h$ is the height.
The volume of a cone is given by $V=\frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h$.
Since the cone and the cylinder have the same radius and height, we can express the volume of the cone in terms of the volume of the cylinder:
\begin{align*}
V_{\text{cone}} &= \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h \\
&= \frac{1}{3}\pi (r^2 h) \\
&= \frac{1}{3}\pi (V_{\text{cylinder}}) \\
&= \frac{1}{3}\pi (54\pi) \\
&= \boxed{18\pi}.
\end{align*}
