The fly first walks straight across the ceiling to the opposite edge, passing through the center of the circle. The distance across the circle through the center is the diameter, which is twice the radius, so the fly travels $2\cdot 58=116$ feet.

The second part of the journey is straight to another point on the edge of the circle but not back through the center. This distance is a chord of the circle. We can use the Pythagorean theorem to find the length of this chord. Let $c$ be the length of the chord, and let $d$ be the distance from the center of the circle to the chord. Then we have

\begin{align*}
c^2 &= (58)^2 - d^2, \\
c^2 &= 3364 - d^2.
\end{align*}

The third part of the journey is straight back to the original starting point. This distance is a radius of the circle, so it is 58 feet.

The total distance traveled by the fly is the sum of the distances of the three parts:

\begin{align*}
116 + c + 58 &= 174 + c.
\end{align*}

We are given that the third part of the journey was 80 feet long, so $c=80$. Therefore, the total distance traveled by the fly is

\begin{align*}
174 + 80 &= \boxed{254} \text{ feet}.
\end{align*}

Final Answer: The final answer is $254$. I hope it is correct.

