Let $M$ and $N$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{CD}$, respectively.
Since $MN$ is parallel to the $x$-axis, we have $OP\perp MN$.
By the Pythagorean Theorem, we have
\begin{align*}
OP^2 &= OM^2 + MP^2 \\
&= (OM)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{2}\cdot 30\right)^2 \\
&= (OM)^2 + 225.
\end{align*}
Similarly,
\begin{align*}
OP^2 &= ON^2 + NP^2 \\
&= (ON)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{2}\cdot 14\right)^2 \\
&= (ON)^2 + 49.
\end{align*}
Since $OP$ is the same in both cases, we have
\begin{align*}
(OM)^2 + 225 &= (ON)^2 + 49 \\
(OM)^2 - (ON)^2 &= -176 \\
(OM + ON)(OM - ON) &= -176.
\end{align*}
Since $OM$ and $ON$ are both positive, we can divide both sides by $(OM - ON)$ to obtain
\begin{align*}
OM + ON &= \frac{-176}{OM - ON}.
\end{align*}
Since $OM + ON = 12$, we have
\begin{align*}
12 &= \frac{-176}{OM - ON} \\
OM - ON &= \frac{-176}{12} \\
OM - ON &= -\frac{44}{3}.
\end{align*}
Squaring both sides, we get
\begin{align*}
(OM - ON)^2 &= \left(-\frac{44}{3}\right)^2 \\
(OM)^2 - 2(OM)(ON) + (ON)^2 &= \frac{1936}{9} \\
(OM)^2 + (ON)^2 &= \frac{1936}{9} + 2(OM)(ON).
\end{align*}
Since $OP^2 = (OM)^2 + (ON)^2$, we have
\begin{align*}
OP^2 &= \frac{1936}{9} + 2(OM)(ON).
\end{align*}
Substituting $2(OM)(ON) = 12(OM - ON)$, we get
\begin{align*}
OP^2 &= \frac{1936}{9} + 12(OM - ON) \\
&= \frac{1936}{9} + 12\left(-\frac{44}{3}\right) \\
&= \frac{1936}{9} - 176 \\
&= \frac{1936 - 1584}{9} \\
