The side length of the largest square is equal to the distance between the two points $(0,10-s)$ and $(10,10-s)$. Using the distance formula, we have

\begin{align*}
s&=\sqrt{(10-0)^2 + ((10-s)-(10-s))^2}\\
&=\sqrt{100 + s^2}\\
\Rightarrow s^2&=100+s^2\\
\Rightarrow s&=10.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the side length of the largest square that can be inscribed in the space inside the square and outside of the triangles is $\boxed{10}$. I hope it is correct.The answer is: 10

